   <mods:abstract>If this letter should find John Jay anxious and preoccupied by the affairs
            ofCongress, he should put it in his pocket until he takes his Sunday ride. "Andwhen you
            have seated yourself on the banks of the Schuylkill, with your pipe inyour mouth, your
            Eyes on the water, and your thoughts everywhere for want ofactivity, take this out ...
            for it will lead your wandering thoughts to thoseboyish days which afford ... pleasure
            in the reflection."Now that John Jay, having read on to this point in the letter, is
            entirely atLivingston's mercy, he should take time to thoroughly reflect on youth as
            theseason of happiness and virtue and on the necessity of avoiding the sourness ofage.
            Livingston hopes soon to receive John Jay's acknowledgment for having given himsuch
            philosophical subjects to reflect upon.</mods:abstract>
